And now, what I want to do is

00:40:14.880 --> 00:40:18.440
highlight what the improvements have
been. So, the first thing that

00:40:18.440 --> 00:40:38.013
Coolidge did is he used a
bona fide vacuum tube.

00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:06.000
He got the gas pressure way,
way down. And, this did two things.

00:40:06.000 --> 00:40:10.000
First of all, there's no glow in
the visible. And secondly,

00:40:10.000 --> 00:40:14.000
it's a much higher efficiency
because when you have glow,

00:40:14.000 --> 00:40:18.000
what it means is that some of those
electrons leaving the cathode are

00:40:18.000 --> 00:40:22.000
not getting to the anode.
They are colliding with gas

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:26.000
molecules and consuming their energy.
So, by the time they get to the

00:40:26.000 --> 00:40:30.000
anode, they don't have enough punch
to kick out inner shell electrons.

00:40:30.000 --> 00:40:53.750
So, the vacuum tube is an
improvement. The second thing is

00:40:53.750 --> 00:41:13.600
hot cathode. What happens with a
hot cathode? You know,

00:40:37.500 --> 00:41:01.250
you have to rip the electrons out of
the cathode. And the electrons are

00:41:01.250 --> 00:41:21.100
bound. So, if you raise the
temperature of the cathode,

00:40:45.000 --> 00:41:08.750
the thermal energy then weakens the
bonds. And so,

00:41:08.750 --> 00:41:28.600
it takes less Coulombic force to rip
the electrons out.

00:40:52.500 --> 00:41:16.250
Now, how's he going to heat the
cathode? Let's think about this.

00:41:16.250 --> 00:41:36.233
You can't use a torch because
you've got a vacuum inside.

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:23.330
So, a torch won't work in a vacuum.
So, I wonder, maybe if I passed a

00:41:23.330 --> 00:41:26.660
current, and sure enough,
what he does is he's got a second

00:41:26.660 --> 00:41:29.990
power supply. You see,
here's the anode over here.

00:41:29.990 --> 00:41:33.320
Here's the cathode, and there's the
30,000, 40,000 volts between the

00:41:33.320 --> 00:41:36.660
cathode and the anode.
